1. Initialize a new Git repository in a folder
named practice-repo and make your first
commit with a sample file.
Commands
mkdir practice-repo
cd practice-repo
git init
echo "Hello Git" > sample.txt
git add sample.txt
git commit -m "First commit"
Explanation
●
●
●
●
●
●
mkdir practice-repo → Creates a new folder named practice-repo.
cd practice-repo → Moves into the folder.
git init → Initializes an empty Git repository.
echo "Hello Git" > sample.txt → Creates a sample file.
git add sample.txt → Adds the file to staging area.
git commit -m "First commit"
→ Saves the file permanently in Git repository.

2. Create a local project, connect it to a
newly created GitHub repository, and push
the project files.
Commands
mkdir myproject
cd myproject
git init
echo "Project File" > index.txt
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"
git remote add origin https://github.com/username/repository.git
git push -u origin main
Explanation
●
●
●
●
●
git init → Creates local Git repository.
git add . → Adds all files.
git commit → Saves changes locally.
git remote add origin → Connects local repository to GitHub repository.
git push -u origin main → Uploads local project files to GitHub.

3. Make a change to a file in your GitHub
repository and pull the updated version
into your local system.
Commands
git pull origin main
Explanation
●
git pull origin main → Downloads latest changes from GitHub and updates local
repository files.

4. Clone a GitHub repository to your local
machine and verify that the project files
are available.
Commands
git clone https://github.com/username/repository.git
cd repository
ls
Explanation
●
●
●
git clone → Copies the GitHub repository into local system.
cd repository → Opens cloned repository.
ls → Displays all files in repository.

5. Clone a repository, create a new file,
and commit the changes locally.
Commands
git clone https://github.com/username/repository.git
cd repository
echo "New File Content" > newfile.txt
git add newfile.txt
git commit -m "Added new file"
Explanation
●
●
●
●
git clone → Downloads repository locally.
echo → Creates a new file.
git add → Adds new file to staging area.
git commit → Saves changes in local repository.

6. Create a new branch, make some
changes in a file, and commit them in that
branch.
Commands
git checkout -b feature-branch
echo "Feature branch content" > branch.txt
git add branch.txt
git commit -m "Changes in feature branch"
Explanation
●
●
●
●
git checkout -b feature-branch → Creates and switches to a new branch.
echo → Creates or modifies file.
git add → Stages changes.
git commit → Saves changes in the branch.

7. Create two branches from main, make
separate changes, and merge both
branches back into main.
Commands
git checkout -b branch1
echo "Branch1 data" > file1.txt
git add .
git commit -m "Branch1 changes"
git checkout main
git checkout -b branch2
echo "Branch2 data" > file2.txt
git add .
git commit -m "Branch2 changes"
git checkout main
git merge branch1
git merge branch2
Explanation
●
Creates two separate branches from main.
●
●
●
Makes different changes in each branch.
Commits changes separately.
Merges both branches back into main branch.

8. Create a feature branch, update a file,
commit the changes, and merge the
branch successfully.
Commands
git checkout -b feature
echo "Updated content" >> sample.txt
git add sample.txt
git commit -m "Updated sample file"
git checkout main
git merge feature
Explanation
●
●
●
●
●
git checkout -b feature → Creates feature branch.
>> → Appends content to existing file.
git add → Stages modified file.
git commit → Saves changes.
git merge feature → Merges feature branch into main branch.

9. Fork a public GitHub repository, clone
your fork locally, and check the configured
remotes.
Commands
git clone https://github.com/yourusername/forked-repo.git
cd forked-repo
git remote -v
Explanation
●
●
●
Forking creates personal copy of repository on GitHub.
git clone → Downloads forked repository.
git remote -v → Displays remote repository links.

10. Fork a repository, make a local change,
commit it, and push the update to your
fork.
Commands
echo "Updated content" >> file.txt
git add file.txt
git commit -m "Updated file"
git push origin main
Explanation
●
●
●
●
Modifies file content.
Adds updated file to staging area.
Commits changes locally.
Pushes updates to forked GitHub repository.

11. Fork a repository, add the original
repository as upstream, and pull the latest
changes.
Commands
git remote add upstream https://github.com/originalowner/repository.git
git fetch upstream
git pull upstream main
Explanation
●
●
●
git remote add upstream → Links original repository.
git fetch upstream → Downloads latest updates.
git pull upstream main → Merges updates into local repository.

12. Create a branch in a cloned repository,
make changes, commit them, merge the
branch, and push the final version.
Commands
git checkout -b newbranch
echo "New changes" > update.txt
git add update.txt
git commit -m "Added update file"
git checkout main
git merge newbranch
git push origin main
Explanation
●
●
●
●
●
Creates new branch.
Makes changes in repository.
Saves changes using commit.
Merges branch into main.
Pushes final updated project to GitHub.
